# Security Hardening Rules

This rule applies when working on security-sensitive code.

## Security Framework Overview

30 security components in `src/slskd/Common/Security/`:

### Foundation (Phase 1)
- `PathGuard.cs` - Directory traversal prevention
- `ContentSafety.cs` - Magic byte verification
- `ViolationTracker.cs` - Auto-escalating bans
- `NetworkGuard.cs` - Rate limiting

### Trust & Verification (Phase 2-3)
- `CryptographicCommitment.cs` - Bait-and-switch prevention
- `ByzantineConsensus.cs` - Multi-source verification
- `PeerReputation.cs` - Behavioral scoring

### Intelligence (Phase 4)
- `Honeypot.cs` - Decoy files
- `CanaryTraps.cs` - Leak tracking

## Required Practices

### Path Handling
- Always use `PathGuard.NormalizeAndValidate()` for user-provided paths
- Never trust Base64-decoded paths without validation
- Check for `..` traversal after URL decoding

### File Operations
- Use `ContentSafety` to verify file types match extensions
- Check for executable content (PE/ELF/Mach-O headers)
- Validate file sizes before processing

### Concurrency
- Use `SemaphoreSlim` for download worker pools
- Cap parallel operations at 10-20 workers
- Never spawn unbounded `Task.Run` loops

### Event Logging
- Use `SecurityEventSink.Report()` for all security events
- Include: event type, severity, message, IP, username
- Subscribe to `HighSeverityEvent` for critical alerts

## Testing Requirements

- Add tests for path traversal attempts
- Test with malformed/malicious inputs
- Verify rate limiting behavior
- Test ban escalation logic

## Integration Checklist

When adding security to a new area:

1. [ ] Add PathGuard validation for file paths
2. [ ] Add ContentSafety checks for downloads
3. [ ] Wire ViolationTracker for abuse detection
4. [ ] Add PeerReputation updates for transfer outcomes
5. [ ] Log security events to SecurityEventSink
6. [ ] Add unit tests for edge cases
